What is CloudFront in AWS?

Amazon CloudFront is a CDN (Content Delivery Network) service that delivers content to users faster by caching it at edge locations closer to them.

Problem Without CloudFront

User in India
    │
    │  every request travels all the way
    ▼
Server in US (S3 / EC2)
    │
    ▼
Response travels back to India

Result:
  ❌ High latency (slow)
  ❌ High load on origin server
  ❌ Bad user experience

Solution With CloudFront

User in India
    │
    ▼
CloudFront Edge Location (Mumbai)  ← closest location
    │
    ├── content cached here? → serve directly ✅ (fast!)
    │
    └── not cached? → fetch from US origin once
                      then cache for next users ✅

How CloudFront Works?

Step 1 — First Request:
User → CloudFront Edge → Cache MISS → fetch from Origin → cache it → serve user

Step 2 — Subsequent Requests:
User → CloudFront Edge → Cache HIT → serve directly (no origin call) ✅

CloudFront Edge Locations

CloudFront has 400+ Edge Locations worldwide:

Americas        Europe          Asia
──────────      ──────────      ──────────
New York        London          Mumbai      ← your instance
Los Angeles     Frankfurt       Singapore     is in us-east-2c
São Paulo       Paris           Tokyo         but users in India
                Amsterdam       Sydney        hit Mumbai edge ✅

Yes! CloudFront is NOT enabled by default — You need to set it up

By Default — Without CloudFront

Your Setup (default):
  S3 Bucket / EC2 / ALB
      │
      └── users access directly
          no caching, no CDN ❌

How to Enable CloudFront — Step by Step  ?

Case 1 — CloudFront for S3 (Static Website)
Step 1 — Go to CloudFront Console

AWS Console
    │
    ▼
Search "CloudFront"
    │
    ▼
Click "Create Distribution"

Step 2 — Set Origin (your S3 bucket)

Origin Domain  →  select your S3 bucket
                  myapp-bucket.s3.amazonaws.com

Origin Access  →  select "Origin Access Control (OAC)"
                  (keeps S3 private, only CloudFront can access) ✅

Step 3 — Cache Settings

Cache Policy       →  CachingOptimized (recommended)
Compress Objects   →  Yes (gzip compression)
Viewer Protocol    →  Redirect HTTP to HTTPS ✅

Step 4 — Settings

Step 5 — Create Distribution

Click "Create Distribution"
    │
    ▼
Takes 5-10 minutes to deploy worldwide
    │
    ▼
You get a domain:
  d1234abcd.cloudfront.net  ✅

Case 2 — CloudFront for EC2 / ALB

Once enabled, users hit CloudFront edge locations instead of your origin directly — faster, safer, cheaper ✅


